{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17563574","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17563574"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T23:00:53+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T23:00:53+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16818"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16818","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16818"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.01,0.13,0.06,0.37,0.43]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9509"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112759"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9509","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9509"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16818"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94793"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"10"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"225"},{"type":"tags","id":"1027"},{"type":"tags","id":"2982"},{"type":"tags","id":"3283"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22448"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28605"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28682"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32561"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32948"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33832"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34881"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46357"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112759","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/112759"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 24-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department accompanied by his parent with concerns about his behaviour over the past six months. He has become increasingly withdrawn, spending most of his time alone in his room. He has dropped out of university and lost contact with his friends. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears dishevelled with poor eye contact. His pulse rate is 82/min, blood pressure 118/74 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. His speech is slow with increased latency. Throughout the interview his face remains almost still with the muscles around his eyes and mouth shifting very little. His voice is even with low inflection and gestures are sparse. Even when discussing personally salient topics, changes in expression are slight and brief: there is a fleeting half-smile when recalling past hobbies and a quiet sigh about leaving university. He denies suicidal ideation.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes this patient\u0027s affect?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Inappropriate affect","Constricted affect","Labile affect","Flat affect","Blunted affect"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient demonstrates features of \u003Cstrong\u003Eblunted affect\u003C/strong\u003E, characterised by reduced emotional expressiveness with minimal changes in facial expression, voice tone, and gesturing. This is a common negative symptom in schizophrenia and can also occur in severe depression. While some emotional expression remains present (occasional slight smiles, sighing), it is significantly diminished.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFlat affect\u003C/strong\u003E represents a more severe form where there is complete or near-complete absence of emotional expression. This patient still demonstrates some degree of emotional expression through occasional smiles and sighs, making blunted affect a more accurate description.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELabile affect\u003C/strong\u003E refers to rapid, exaggerated changes in emotional expression that are unstable and may appear out of proportion to the situation. This pattern is not demonstrated in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInappropriate affect\u003C/strong\u003E describes emotional expressions that are incongruent with the context or content of speech, such as laughing while discussing sad topics. This patient\u0027s affect, while reduced, remains appropriate to the context.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EConstricted affect\u003C/strong\u003E refers to a mild reduction in the range and intensity of emotional expression. This term would understate the degree of affective flattening observed in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe assessment of affect requires careful observation of multiple channels of emotional expression including facial movements, voice tone, and body language. Changes in affect can provide important diagnostic clues in psychiatric assessment, particularly in differentiating between conditions such as schizophrenia, depression, and other mood disorders.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Blunted affect is a reduction in emotional expressiveness commonly seen in schizophrenia and depression.","Assessment of affect requires observation of facial expression, tone of voice, and body language.","Flat affect is more severe than blunted affect and involves complete absence of emotional expression."],"references":["Grigoriou M, Upthegrove R. Blunted affect and suicide in schizophrenia: A systematic review. Psychiatry Research. 2020 Nov 1;293:113355.","Sadock BJ, Sadock VA, Ruiz P. Kaplan and Sadock\u0027s comprehensive textbook of psychiatry. lippincott Williams \u0026 wilkins; 2017 May 11."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94793"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16818"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","i